text:
To everyone confused with the comments: When this video first came out people started to give a lot of criticisms, so Disney started to delete it all at the same time that a bunch of similar positive comments started to appear saying ‘I love when Ariel did this’ ‘I love when they’ve done that’ etc.. so instead of saying what they meant, they started to play along by saying they loved something that isn’t there, to mock/protest. 

It also seem be a reference to LOTR’s ‘Evil cannot create anything new, they can only corrupt and ruin good forces have invented or made’ because Disney/Hollywood doesn’t (seem to) do this because they care, but because they want easy money and praise while not creating anything new, because apparantly ‘poc’ and women aren’t worth the risk, so by making parodies of already established franchises, they get points with people who are nostalgic and who want representation, while not putting up the work.

text: Also the point behind the format they're using is to mock the fact that basically the big companies in these kinds of films are counting on nostalgia for previous (good) films to get people excited about their new film. Basically people are tired of seeing films/shows that are a derivative of something else, and of much lesser quality. So that's why the comments are referencing things from other films- because it doesn't matter what film it was in, as long as it evokes a nostalgic reaction in someone (from the studio perspective). I don't know if I'm explaining this well, lol. But anyway the format's being used for all the new offerings from franchises like Rings of Power, She Hulk, and whatnot- since it's pretty clear these things are being made to capitalize on the franchise's popularity without bothering to make an actual quality product. And it's specifically mocking things like the scene in the Kenobi show where it shows how Luke got a toy that was shown in the first Star Wars film- like, look Audience, you remember that, now clap!

text:
@Lewis Catlord  I think I'll regret this.
The key difference between the three characters you listed and Ariel is that they actually have a specific cultural identity. 

Ariel is from Atlantis, a specifically fictional and fantastical place. It's not Europe and frankly even if it was Europe there have been bipoc Europeans for thousands of years. 

Disney did not invent this story, the first animated version was an adaptation, this is a new adaptation with a different cultural identity for a different time using different techniques. It's not the same film.

text:
I really think some of these people need to quit the act and admit their bias is racially motivated. Poc have grown up absorbing stories and media about characters that weren't their race at all, and still, loved and favored them. There are characters from the past who, were created from a real person yet portrayed in another image (i.e Betty Boop). 

I'm entirely with SOME of y'all on the way modern media just half heartedly throws us reboots with minimal care for the franchises, that they tokenize and don't really care for what they're doing.. But what needs to be nipped in the bud is the hate on Halle Bailey. If a poc can watch and think warmly of non-poc characters, some of y'all really need to tell me why Halle can't be given a chance?? Brandi in Cinderella didn't have people in an uproar.. 

Watching this trailer I just see a new version of Ariel, just another live action princess for ANOTHER Disney fresh take. Complain about Disney's incompetence all you'd like, but don't go making this about Ariel "being black", cause at that point that's all it is. Cinderella is one of my favorite Disney princesses, & she didn't have to be black to be that for me.

text:
@Rakesh Kumar  mermaids aren’t a species, they have no race. What’s integral to her story is her voice, she has to have a beautiful voice because that’s what Ursula is after. The actress has a phenomenal voice.
The Black Panther is a descendent of a hidden African city untouched by outsiders that were given powers by the Egyptian God Bast. Egypt is a country in Africa, and have been historically depicted as individuals with highly melanated skin. The historical accuracy of and African descendant cast as Black Panther is integral to the story. There is no history of mermaids… cause they don’t exist.
author: Melody Sivri

text: @Tom Ayre  would like to add that if there were humans that managed to evolve and live under water (become mermaids) they wouldn’t have any oxygen intake, thus their blood would run blue (oxygenated blood circulates red due to their reaction with iron in blood cell hemoglobin) and their skin would have no pigmentation due to the lack of sun. Essentially they would be translucent blue beings… if they were real.

text:
@Melody Valentine   hi name twin! To clarify though, Elsa’s city of Arendelle is fictional but based on Norwegian influences. You’re absolutely right in questioning why she shouldn’t be portrayed as a black woman, but to reiterate my point, mermaids are not real and have no race. I’m sure they could have, but they wanted to connect her to a historical Norway. Although Ariel’s story is also based off of Hans Christian Andersen’s morbid story from the last 1800’s (presumed to be located between Denmark and Norway), the modernization of this tale is all up to how it’s interpreted. If we literally interpreted the original content, there would be no fans at all. Every live action Disney classic has been changed, they are not exact replicas of their animated films… so it’s strange as to why people are making a massive deal of it.

I also respect your opinion on her appearance, but it really isn’t kind of you to say that she looks like a male animated fish. We are all women and beautiful, powerful, kind, and above all respectful of one another. At least we should be. This actress is beautiful and has an absolutely stunning voice. I’m glad she is the new vision and VOICE of Ariel. The entire premise of her story is how she is a young lady deprived of her VOICE in her own life.

text: @Tom Ayre  I don't think the Little Mermaid was ever specified as being from Atlantis. Of course she was also never specified as being red haired, or having hair of any particular color, or having a name other than the Little Mermaid... Her skin was described as "pale" & her eyes were described as "blue". The story was written by Danish author Hans Christian Andersen in 1837 when Denmark had, as it still does today, a decidedly monochromatic population, lol. I think the original mythology of mermaids is also from this area from the seventh or eighth centuries. This wouldn't be the first time Disney was in the hot seat for changing a key characteristic of this iconic character. Remember the outrage when they dared cast a blonde actress to play Ariel? Or when Columbia tried to cast a brunette in the role of Annie? Ha ha ha. I think Disney should make a Little Mermaid movie following the original story.... Maybe not for children, lol. What do you think? If I'm  not remembering the original Little Mermaid correctly please let me know.

author: Nancy D'Addario

text:
@dragonsman   I've said this in a different thread and I'll say it again here: 
The Little Mermaid was written by a Dane, but does not take place in Denmark. It was actually set in the southern Italy/Malta region.  Andersen had visited there just a few years before publishing The Little Mermaid, and the descriptions from the original (from the sea to the landscape and architecture) match the Mediterranean and not Denmark at all. Even the prince is described as having black hair and eyes. It also isn't classified as a folktale.  The story was from Andersen's imagination (not passed down orally), and was partially inspired by the story Undine.
Even the Disney version (which departs greatly from the source material), doesn't have anything particularly Danish about it.
So yeah. Say what you want about the new Ariel, but Danish culture or depriving Danes of roles shouldn't really factors here.

text:
@Nesrovlah survivalist  Then you didn’t see what they were trying to convey.

The rookie team was there to remind him that he too was once a rookie, that he isn’t perfect, but that he still managed to become who he is despite his shortcomings, and so can they, if someone is willing to believe in them like his friend did.

Zorg is also interesting, because he presents a dilema that many of us have thought about, what if you had the chance to correct that one mistake that continues to haunt you? What if you could just change that and be happy? Would you do it? Even if it meant erasing everything you have up to this point in time in your life? 

I wish I could say I am sure what my answer would be, but I am not, and I guess that is why it stroke a nerve with me.

text:
@Natasha  что есть развитие? развитие есть переход от старого к новому, и не всегда оно является положительным. Есть такое понятие как «регрессивное развитие». и сейчас я докажу тебе, Наташа, почему это именно регресс. Одна из самых ранних легенд о русалках появилась в Сирии около 1000 г. до н.э., когда богиня Атаргатис нырнула в озеро, чтобы принять форму рыбы. выглядит эта сирийская богиня, как идеал женщины, с идеальным белоснежным телом и миловидным личиком. Сейчас же нам пытаются сказать, что она выглядит, как некрасивая чернокожая женщина. Глупые люди называют это свободой, но это не свобода, это промывание мозгов и навязывание нетрадиционных ценностей в ДЕТСКОМ мультике. за это должны судить, но в крайне либеральной Америке, за это еще и наградят. я рад, что бОльшая часть восприняла этот фильм отрицательно, значит не все потеряно, но я боюсь, что такими темпами последующие поколения будут все больше отдаляться от моральных ценностей и здравого смысла

author: Hitter Fatter

text:
You know what they could have done instead?

Making this mermaid character an original character. She's a mermaid princess in a mermaid kingdom located near Africa and she falls in love with a human. After hearing the story of another mermaid from the other side of the world that successfully got to be with her human love years ago, she uses this as a motivation to try to be with her human love too, because if that mermaid can why couldn't she? Fast forward, after all the hardships and trials, she finally gets to have a happy ending with her human love. 

Then as the movie nears to an end, we then see a huge sailing ship and on it we see a red-haired woman looking through a telescope. Then a child's voice calls for her,  "Mama" and she turns around, revealing a beautiful woman with blue eyes. A red-haired child runs up to her and she carries the child. Then we hear a man's voice call to her, "Ariel, what are you looking at?", and then we see this handsome man with a younger red-haired child riding on his shoulder. This scene finally confirms that the movie took place in Ariel's world, that the story about the mermaid from the other side of the world was actually about Ariel, and what we just saw was Ariel and Eric and their two children, still happily married after all these years and are currently traveling around the world. This also confirms that there are other mermaid kingdoms with different cultures existing all around the world. And the film finally ends.

text:
@ChaoticAngelKitten  He did not.  To answer your questions:  
He wrote about a widowed and unnamed Sea King and his 6 daughters.  His mother (their grandmother) was also a part of the story, and she told the youngest daughter (the unnamed Little Mermaid) about the surface world.  His daughters were said to sing, but singing is a common trope among many different culture's mermaid myths. They did live in a palace (as they were mermaid royalty), but it was made of coral, not gold like in Greek myth.  And they were not gods or immortal. In HCA's story they lived to 300 years old and had no immortal soul (unlike humans in the story).

text:
​ @Dust  
Most people are doing it cause they think it's funny. And that's it.

Some people are doing it cause they are unhappy with the decisions being made for this movie, and they know their negative comments are being intentionally suppressed by YouTube. So they are trying to express their displeasure in the only way that YouTube can't stop them--by making these kinds of joke comments.

And an even smaller number of people are doing it purely to expose how Disney clearly has some kind of deal with YouTube to ensure that all the top comments exclusively contain positive messages, such as "I love the part where" etc. I suspect these are the people who started the meme.

text: @MoonwalkerWorshiper  I'll explain. It's a form of modern absurdist humor, used to satirise the trailer and the company's agenda as a whole. The joke is closely related to the memes that emerged following the failure of Morbious. The principle is that there is no public appetite for these films, and thus, with false enthusiasm people clamour about their excitement for scenes and lines from other, better and older productions. Comments critising productions like this are removed with incredible speed, so these comments form a kind of dissenting dogwhistle that only people in the know can understand.

text: I think the real reason Disney keeps on changing the race of old characters instead of making new original ones is because the audience doesn’t really care about the new characters for example in the Aladdin remake they introduced dalia jasmine’s handmaiden but did anyone really find her that interesting? She was mostly just a minor character that was brought in because there were barely any female characters in the animated one besides jasmine. but for me I don’t think the real issue is the race swapping I think it’s the live action remakes in general Disney just needs to stop remaking stuff we’ve already seen before and just focus on new stuff but even if they did create an original character for Halle to play the audience would just see her as just another minor character that anyone could care less about but when you think about it does Ariel being black now effect the storyline? I mean do they even mention the color of her skin in the animated film? I mean she still looks like Ariel she has the green tail, the purple bra, the red hair, but even if they did cast a white actress as Ariel would people still be interested in seeing the movie? Yet again I really do think it’s just that everyone is getting sick and tired of the remakes sure maybe they were fun to watch at first but after years and years of seeing the same thing basically shot for shot people would rather just see a new animated story instead.

Really?  I'm just an actress,  I love what I do. I am proud of my work, despite the fact that some of you criticize me based only my color,  or perhaps just for the love of trolling?  
Even though I understand some levels of trolling, sometimes it is a harsh reality of being able to comment anonymously, sometimes it can be funny, sometimes especially when it is directed at one person, and all of the sudden, THAT person is you, it kind of hurts... I'm just a little girl,  and it hurts... it really does"
 Then a single tear falls from her eye, and trickles down down her cheek. 
Suddenly.... her eyes start glowing red and she starts laser blasting random You tubers like "brrrtzzztt!  Brrrrrrtzzzzt!  Brrrzzzzttt!!!!"
I love that part

text:
Are those activists at Dismal getting fired yet? They managed to destroy the billion dollar Star Wars franchise; continue to remake vastly inferior woke versions of old successful movies, which invariably lose tons of money. 

Maybe Disney is now a nonprofit social justice activist organization instead of a movie studio, and are using their losses as tax write-offs or money laundering? If they’re still a movie studio, I’ll simplify it for them: make good movies with interesting characters that people like, then receive profits. 

It’s not any more complicated than that. Since about 5% of people are actual leftist lunatics who are obsessed with ‘representation,’ and those people don’t have money to see movies, who do you expect to actually put money down for this condescending, virtue-signalling nonsense?
